1422","1426":"1426","abt 1424":"about 1424","1424":"1424","1401":"1401","abt 1426":"about 1426","1466":"1466","1422":"1422","1464":"1464","1419":"1419","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","of Dunstable, Beds., Eng.":"Dunstable, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","of Stepney, Middx., Eng.":"Stepney, London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chedworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Chisworth (Derbys)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Johanna Chedworth was born in 1401, in Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir William Marrow III in 1415, in London, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1466, in London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1401–1466":"1401–1466","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1419–1464":"1419–1464","1422–Male":"1422–Surnud","1424–Male":"1424–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","11 January 1464":"11. jaanuar 1464","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","abt 1422":"umbes 1422","1426":"1426","abt 1424":"umbes 1424","1424":"1424","1401":"1401","abt 1426":"umbes 1426","1466":"1466","1422":"1422","1464":"1464","1419":"1419","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","of Dunstable, Beds., Eng.":"Dunstable, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Stepney, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Stepney, Middx., Eng.":"Stepney, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1401–1466":"1401–1466","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1419–1464":"1419–1464","1422–Male":"1422–Kuollut","1424–Male":"1424–Kuollut","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","11 January 1464":"11. tammikuuta 1464","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","abt 1422":"noin 1422","1426":"1426","abt 1424":"noin 1424","1424":"1424","1401":"1401","abt 1426":"noin 1426","1466":"1466","1422":"1422","1464":"1464","1419":"1419","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","of Dunstable, B